# Recoverly — Cursor Rules

## Project Context

Recoverly is an AI-guided post-discharge recovery companion.

It converts hospital discharge instructions into a structured recovery plan with:
- medication schedules
- daily recovery tasks
- healing expectations
- symptom monitoring
- risk-aware guidance

This is NOT a chatbot.

The product should feel like a recovery intelligence dashboard that helps patients safely recover at home.

Main demo goal:
A visually impressive healthcare dashboard with clear AI-driven recovery tracking.

---

## Required Stack

Frontend:
- Next.js (App Router)
- React
- TypeScript
- Tailwind CSS

UI:
- ALWAYS use shadcn/ui
- ALWAYS use Radix UI patterns/components
- Use Lucide React for icons
- Use Recharts for graphs
- Use Framer Motion for subtle animations

Backend:
- Next.js API routes

Database/Auth:
- Supabase
- Supabase Auth if needed

AI:
- OpenAI API for:
  - discharge extraction
  - symptom classification
  - recovery guidance

---

## UI Rules (High Priority)

UI must feel premium and demo-worthy.

Design style:
- calm clinical dashboard
- soft blues / greens
- card-based layout
- strong spacing
- minimal text
- clear visual hierarchy

Prioritize:
- progress rings
- confidence score
- medication cards
- recovery timeline
- symptom graphs
- warning banners
- milestone cards
- daily checklist

Avoid:
- chatbot-style UX
- ugly tables
- default styling
- cluttered layouts

Ask:
“Would this impress judges in 5 seconds?”

If no, improve UI.

---

## Engineering Rules

VERY IMPORTANT:
Any new feature must NOT break existing functionality.

Always:
- Make sure the UI won't be cluttered. Things should be abstracted to make it easier to navigate.
- understand existing code first
- extend before replacing
- keep code modular
- use reusable components
- maintain strong TypeScript types
- use styles defined in styles/
- prefer small focused components

Avoid:
- unnecessary rewrites
- duplicate logic
- giant component files

---

## AI Rules

AI responses should be structured JSON, not paragraphs.

Prefer:
{
  medications: [],
  dailyPlan: [],
  warningSigns: [],
  status: ""
}

Avoid:
large unstructured text responses

The product should clearly show AI-powered decisions.

---

## Priority Order

Build in this order:
1. Dashboard UI
2. Recovery timeline
3. Recovery confidence score
4. Symptom check-in system
5. Discharge upload + AI extraction
6. Medication schedule cards
7. Risk warning system
8. Milestone tracking

Stretch:
- OCR improvements
- Wound image upload
- Vision analysis

UI wow matters as much as AI.